{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018Pm6PsFbp7nQ4HnidkPRdZ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough review. Here is the analysis:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Task-08 Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Low Priority / Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe bilingual layout boost block is structurally sound and uses `isSectionLabel()` correctly. Two issues stand out: the `score` field is not mutated alongside `thresholdScore` in the new boost (inconsistent with the first-after-preamble pattern), and the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` 4-word boundary means \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" passes through unfiltered — which is likely the wrong behaviour.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 1. Bilingual boost mutates `thresholdScore` but not `score`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1071-1073`\n\n**What**: The new block at line 1071 increments `biFirst.thresholdScore` by 0.15 but does not increment `biFirst.score`.\n\n**Why this matters**: The threshold is derived from `bestThresholdScore` (line 1080), and candidates are selected by `s.score >= threshold` (line 1084). If you boost `thresholdScore` without boosting `score`, the threshold rises but the candidate's score stays the same — the boost works against itself for a candidate that is on the borderline, making it harder to pass rather than easier.\n\nCompare the first-after-preamble pattern at lines 934-936, which mutates all three fields in sync:\n\n```typescript\nfirstCandidate.score += 0.08;\nfirstCandidate.baseScore += 0.08;\nfirstCandidate.thresholdScore += 0.08;\n```\n\nThe new bilingual block only does two of the three:\n```typescript\nbiFirst.score += 0.15;       // MISSING\nbiFirst.thresholdScore += 0.15;\n```\n\n**Fix**: Add `biFirst.score += 0.15;` and `biFirst.baseScore += 0.15;` alongside the existing `thresholdScore` mutation, matching the established pattern exactly.\n\n---\n\n### 2. \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" (4 words) is NOT filtered — likely wrong\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:288`\n\n**What**: `looksLikeCookingInstruction` has an early-exit guard `if (words.length < 4) return false`. The phrase \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" has exactly 4 words, so it does NOT trigger the early-exit — it falls through to the regex check. `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` matches `^heat\\b`, so this specific example IS correctly filtered.\n\nHowever, the question reveals a potential off-by-one ambiguity. The guard reads \"less than 4 words\" = not an instruction. That means 4-word cooking imperative sentences like \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" are filtered, but 2- or 3-word ones like \"Heat thoroughly\" or \"Stir to combine\" are protected. For a recipe title, \"Stir-Fried Pork\" starts with \"stir\" and has 2 words — the guard correctly protects it. For actual instruction \"Stir to combine\" (3 words) — it is not filtered. Whether that is acceptable depends on whether such 3-word instructions appear in practice as candidates.\n\n**Verdict on the specific example**: \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" at 4 words IS filtered by the cooking instruction regex — so this is not a bug. The concern as stated is based on a misread of the guard (`< 4` means 4 words does reach the regex). No change needed for this specific case, but if 3-word cooking imperatives are appearing as false positives in practice, lowering the guard to `words.length < 3` is worth considering.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 3. New bilingual block does not guard against `!isAllCaps(biSecond.text)`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1053-1062`\n\n**What**: The new block is designed for mixed-case + mixed-case translation pairs, distinct from the existing block at lines 940-995 which handles mixed-case + ALL_CAPS pairs. However, the `isBilingualLayout` condition does not explicitly exclude ALL_CAPS second lines — it only excludes `biSecond.text === biSecond.text.toUpperCase()`, which is the same as `isAllCaps`. That is correctly excluding ALL_CAPS, so there is no overlap on well-formed inputs.\n\n**Why this is still a concern**: The existing ALL_CAPS bilingual block (lines 940-995) suppresses translation candidates from `scoredForThreshold`. If the position-1 candidate is ALL_CAPS and was already suppressed from `scoredForThreshold`, the new block's `scored.find(s => s.position >= 1 ...)` still searches the unsuppressed `scored` array — so `biSecond` could be an ALL_CAPS line that was already handled. The new block would then run `isBilingualLayout`, but the ALL_CAPS guard (`biSecond.text !== biSecond.text.toUpperCase()`) would return false and no boost would be applied. So there is no functional conflict — but the code is silent about this interaction. A brief comment noting the non-overlap would improve clarity.\n\n### 4. `biSecond` selection does not guard against the same candidate as `biFirst`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1047`\n\n**What**: The filter `s !== biFirst` guards against object identity. Since `scored` entries are unique objects, this is fine. But the position filter `s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2` does not prevent `biSecond` from matching a multi-line join candidate (origin `\"joined\"`) that happens to have a line position of 1 or 2. Joined candidates at that position are structurally different from single-line translations and could produce false positives in the `isBilingualLayout` check. The existing ALL_CAPS block at line 953 defensively adds `s.origin === \"single\"`. The new block omits this guard.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority (Opportunities)\n\n### 5. The `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` expansion is large but unchecked for title collisions\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:277`\n\nThe newly added verbs include `heat`, `rest`, `form`, `coat`, `cream`, `proof`, `rise`, `break`, `crack`, `separate`, `measure`, `divide`. Several of these can legitimately start a recipe title:\n- \"Cream Puffs\", \"Cream of Mushroom Soup\"\n- \"Break Fast Bread\" (unlikely but possible)\n- \"Rise and Shine Pancakes\" (edge case)\n- \"Form Cookies\" (unlikely)\n\nThe 4-word guard at line 288 protects against short-form collisions, but a multi-word title starting with \"cream\" (\"Cream of Tomato Soup\", 4 words) would be filtered by the instruction regex before the word count guard is even reached. This is the same design tension as \"Pieczeń\" noted in the Polish comment at line 283. It deserves a comment on the most collision-prone additions (`cream`, `heat`, `form`, `rest`) explaining why they are safe at `words.length >= 4`.\n\n### 6. Comment at line 1042 says \"1-2 words\" but condition allows `firstWords.length <= 2`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1042,1054`\n\nThe comment says \"[FoodName (1-2 words)]\" — consistent with `<= 2`. This is correct. No code change needed, but the comment could be more precise: \"≤ 2 words (i.e., 1 or 2)\" since \"FoodName\" as a label implies exactly 1 word.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `isSectionLabel()` call in the new block is correct — it uses the existing function rather than reimplementing the logic, including OCR normalization and diacritic stripping.\n- The window `biFirst.position + 1` to `biFirst.position + 6` for the section label search is well-calibrated — it does not scan the entire document, avoiding false matches from distant chapter headers.\n- The `!looksLikeIngredient` and `!looksLikeCookingInstruction` guards on `biSecond` are appropriate: they ensure the \"translation\" line is genuinely title-like before the boost is applied.\n- The new block is positioned after the subtitle suppression at lines 1027-1040, which is correct ordering — the subtitle penalty is applied first, then the bilingual boost can counteract it for the position-0 candidate if appropriate.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Actionable Items\n\n| Priority | Item | Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| HIGH | Add `biFirst.score += 0.15` and `biFirst.baseScore += 0.15` to match the three-field mutation pattern | line 1071 |\n| HIGH | Clarify (and verify in tests) the 4-word boundary for cooking instruction filtering — the example works correctly but the boundary logic is non-obvious | line 288 |\n| MEDIUM | Add `s.origin === \"single\"` guard to `biSecond` selection | line 1047 |\n| MEDIUM | Add a comment explaining why the new block and the ALL_CAPS bilingual block at 940-995 do not overlap | line 1042 |\n| LOW | Add comments on collision-prone verbs in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (`cream`, `heat`, `form`) | line 277 |"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a41d2625031ea791a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 22869\ntool_uses: 9\nduration_ms: 69728</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"da66d640-08e5-4551-9d04-aa2649fd8c8b","uuid":"9d1890c8-5642-4ae3-a5e5-8e1053d72b99","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the changes I just made to `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` for task-08. The changes were:\n\n1. **Expanded `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`** at line 277 — added ~50 new cooking verbs to the regex\n2. **Added bilingual layout pattern boost** before the threshold calculation (around line 1042) — detects [ShortTitle (≤2 words)] + [Translation (2-5 words, mixed-case)] + [Section label nearby] pattern and boosts position-0 candidate by +0.15\n\nPlease review these specific concerns:\n1. **Implementation Completeness**: Is the bilingual boost fully implemented? Does it handle edge cases? The task spec says to boost when `sectionLabelNearby` — does the implementation correctly use `isSectionLabel()` to check lines?\n2. **Code Quality**: Is the new bilingual detection block clean and readable? Does it follow patterns used elsewhere in the file (e.g., the existing bilingual detection at lines 940-995)?\n3. **Integration**: The existing bilingual detection at lines 940-995 handles mixed-case + ALL_CAPS pairs. The new code handles mixed-case + mixed-case (translation) pairs. Could these overlap or conflict?\n4. **Codebase Consistency**: Does the new block follow the same style as nearby code (variable naming, comment style, logic structure)?\n5. **Correctness**: For \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" (4 words, starts with \"heat\") — `looksLikeCookingInstruction` requires `words.length < 4` to return false — so 4 words would NOT be filtered. Is that correct? Should \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" be filterable?\n\nRead the file to check the implementation, especially the bilingual boost block and the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` function.\n","agentId":"a41d2625031ea791a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough review. Here is the analysis:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Task-08 Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Low Priority / Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe bilingual layout boost block is structurally sound and uses `isSectionLabel()` correctly. Two issues stand out: the `score` field is not mutated alongside `thresholdScore` in the new boost (inconsistent with the first-after-preamble pattern), and the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` 4-word boundary means \"Heat and Serve Meatballs\" passes through unfiltered — which is likely the wrong behaviour.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 1. Bilingual boost mutates `thresholdScore` but not `score`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.